# Function Design Rule

When creating or modifying functions, enforce single-responsibility design.

Prefer small, named functions over large multi-phase functions. A function should normally have one primary reason to change.

Split functions that mix validation, retrieval, transformation, persistence, external calls, prompt construction, or presentation.

Do not add new behavior to an already broad function. Extract the relevant phase first, then add the new behavior in the correct layer.

Target 10 to 40 lines per function. Treat 60 lines as a soft limit and 80 lines as a refactor warning.

Use guard clauses to reduce nesting. Target maximum nesting depth of 2.

Comments are not a substitute for extraction. If a function has internal sections such as validate, load, transform, save, those sections should usually become named helpers.

Preserve behavior during refactors. Run or update tests when behavior is not already covered.